<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-03-01T13:23:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-03-01T13:23:00-05:00" n="912" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d912">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.115C96/114</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Hostetter</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Hermosillo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-03-01T11:00:00-07:23">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 1, 1916, 11 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Department’s February 24, 6 p.m. Obregon just arrived and spoke to him
                            about Chihuahua district. Says he has sent additional troops with very
                            good generals, Herrera and Gutiérres, who thoroughly know country, with
                            orders to push pursuit and earnestly hopes to have district cleared very
                            soon.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hostetter</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>